<section xml:id="section-solving-quadratic-equations-by-using-a-square-root">

    <title>Solving Quadratic Equations by Using a Square Root</title>

    <objectives>
        <title>PCC Course Content and Outcome Guide</title>
        <ul>
            <li><xref ref="mth65-solve-quadratic-equations-using-square-root-property" /></li>
            <li><xref ref="mth65-solve-quadratic-equation-applications" /></li>
        </ul>
    </objectives>

    <introduction>
        <p>In <xref ref="section-solving-quadratic-equations-by-factoring">Section</xref>, we learned how to solve quadratic equations by factoring. In this section, we will learn how to solve some special forms of quadratic equations using the <term>square root property</term>. We will also learn how to use the <term>Pythagorean Theorem</term> to find missing sides of a triangle.</p>

        <figure>
            <caption>Alternative Video Lesson</caption>
            <video youtube="clC-aoijpcg"/>
        </figure>
    </introduction>

   <subsection>
        <title>The Pythagorean Theorem</title>
        <p>We will start this section with an important property about right triangles called the <term>Pythagorean Theorem</term>.</p>

        <theorem>The Pythagorean Theorem
            <title>The Pythagorean Theorem</title>
            <p>For any right triangle, the lengths of the three sides have the following relationship: <m>a^2+b^2=c^2</m>. The sides <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> are called <term>legs</term> and the longest side <m>c</m> is called the <term>hypotenuse</term>.</p>
        </theorem>

        <figure>
            <caption>Pythagorean Theorem: In a right triangle, the length of its three sides have the following relationship: <m>a^2+b^2=c^2</m></caption>
            <image width="35%">
                <latex-image-code>
                    <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                        \draw (0,0) -- (3,0) -- (3,4) -- cycle;
                        \draw (3,0.2) -- (2.8,0.2) -- (2.8,0);
                        \draw [below] (1.5,0) node {$a$};
                        \draw [right] (3,2) node {$b$};
                        \draw [right] (1,2) node {$c$};
                    \end{tikzpicture}]]>
                </latex-image-code>
            </image>
        </figure>

        <example>
            <p>Keisha is designing a wooden frame in the shape of a right triangle, as shown. The legs of the triangle are <quantity><mag>3</mag><unit base="foot"/></quantity> and <quantity><mag>4</mag><unit base="foot"/></quantity>. How long should she cut the piece of wood for the diagonal side? Use the Pythagorean Theorem to find the length of the hypotenuse.</p>

            <figure>
                <caption>Pythagorean Theorem Problem</caption>
                <image width="35%">
                    <latex-image-code>
                        <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                          \draw (0,0) node[anchor=north]{$B$}
                              -- (3,0) node[anchor=north]{$C$}
                              -- (3,4) node[anchor=south]{$A$}
                              -- cycle;
                            \draw (3,0.2) -- (2.8,0.2) -- (2.8,0);
                            \draw [below] (1.5,0) node {$a=3$ ft};
                            \draw [right] (3,2) node {$b=4$ ft};
                            \draw [right] (1,2) node {$c$};
                        \end{tikzpicture}]]>
                    </latex-image-code>
                </image>
            </figure>

            <p>According to Pythagorean Theorem, we have:<md>
                <mrow>c^2\amp=a^2+b^2</mrow>
                <mrow>c^2\amp=3^2+4^2</mrow>
                <mrow>c^2\amp=9+16</mrow>
                <mrow>c^2\amp=25</mrow>
                <intertext>Now we have a quadratic equation that we need to solve. We need to find the number that has a square of <m>25</m>. That is what the square root operation does.</intertext>
                <mrow>c\amp=\sqrt{25}</mrow>
                <mrow>c\amp=5</mrow>
            </md>Keisha should cut the diagonal piece to be <quantity><mag>5</mag><unit base="foot"/></quantity> long.</p>

            <p>Note that <m>-5</m> is also a solution of <m>c^2=25</m> because <m>(-5)^2=25</m> but a length cannot be a negative number. We will need to include both solutions when they are relevant.</p>
        </example>
    </subsection>

    <subsection>
        <title>Solving Quadratic Equations Using the Square Root Property</title>

        <p>When we learned how to solve linear equations we used inverse operations to isolate the variable. We will use the same idea here because the square root is the inverse operation of squaring a number. For example, if <m>x^2=9</m>, we can think of undoing the square with the square root. There are two numbers that we can square to get <m>9</m>, however, <m>-3</m> and <m>3</m> so we need to include both solutions.This brings us to the Square Root Property.</p>

        <theorem xml:id="theorem-square-root-property">
        <title>The Square Root Property</title>
        <idx><h>The Square Root Property</h></idx>
        <statement>
            <p>If <m>x^2=k</m> then <m>x=-\sqrt{k}</m> or <m>x=\sqrt{k}</m>. The positive root is called the <term>principal root</term>.</p>
        </statement>
        </theorem>

        <p>Here is another example using the Pythagorean Theorem and the Square Root Property.</p>

        <example>
            <p>A <m>7.5</m>ft ladder is leaning against a wall. The distance from the base of the ladder to the wall is <m>2.1</m> feet. How high on the wall can the ladder reach?</p>

            <figure>
                <caption>Pythagorean Theorem Problem</caption>
                <image width="35%">
                    <latex-image-code>
                        <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                            \draw (0,0) -- (5,0);
                            \draw (5,0) -- (5,10);
                            \draw (2.9,0) -- (5,7.2);
                            \draw (5,0.2) -- (4.8,0.2) -- (4.8,0);
                            \draw [below] (4,0) node {$a=2.1$ ft};
                            \draw [right] (5,3.6) node {$b$};
                            \draw [left] (3.5,3.6) node {$c=7.5$ ft};
                        \end{tikzpicture}]]>
                    </latex-image-code>
                </image>
            </figure>

            <p>To solve this problem, we use Pythagorean Theorem:<md>
                <mrow>a^2+b^2\amp=c^2</mrow>
                <mrow>2.1^2+b^2\amp=7.5^2</mrow>
                <mrow>4.41+b^2\amp=56.25</mrow>
            </md>Now we need to isolate <m>b^2</m> in order to solve for <m>b</m>.<md>
                <mrow>4.41+b^2\subtractright{4.41}\amp=56.25\subtractright{4.41}</mrow>
                <mrow>b^2\amp=51.84</mrow>
            </md>To remove the square, we use the square root property. Because this is a geometric situation we only need to use the principal root:<md>
                <mrow>b^2\amp=51.84</mrow>
                <mrow>b\amp=\sqrt{51.84}</mrow>
                <mrow>b\amp=7.2</mrow>
            </md>Solution: The ladder can reach <m>7.2</m> feet high on the wall.</p>
        </example>
     
        <p>In the geometric scenarios above, we didn't use the negative solutions because negative lengths don't make sense. In the following equations without context, we will write both solutions in a solution set.</p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Solve for <m>y</m> in <m>y^2-49=0</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>Before we use the square root property we need to isolate the squared quantity.<md>
                    <mrow>y^2-49\amp=0</mrow>
                    <mrow>y^2-49\addright{49}\amp=0\addright{49}</mrow>
                    <mrow>y^2\amp=49</mrow></md><md>
                    <mrow>y\amp=-\sqrt{49} \amp\text{ or }\amp\amp y\amp=\sqrt{49}</mrow>
                    <mrow>y\amp=-7\amp\text{ or }\amp\amp y\amp=7</mrow>
                </md>The solution set is <m>\{-7,7\}</m>. </p>

                <p>We can also solve this equation by factoring:<md>
                    <mrow>y^2-49\amp=0</mrow>
                    <mrow>(y+7)(y-7)\amp=0</mrow></md><md>
                    <mrow>y+7\amp=0\amp\text{ or }\amp\amp y-7\amp=0</mrow>
                    <mrow>y\amp=-7\amp\text{ or }\amp\amp y\amp=7</mrow>
                </md>The solution set is <m>\{-7,7\}</m>.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Solve for <m>z</m> in <m>4z^2-81=0</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>Before we use the square root property we need to isolate the squared quantity.<md>
                    <mrow>4z^2-81\amp=0</mrow>
                    <mrow>4z^2\amp=81</mrow>
                    <mrow>\divideunder{4z^2}{4}\amp=\divideunder{81}{4}</mrow>
                    <mrow>z^2\amp=\frac{81}{4}</mrow></md><md>
                    <mrow>z\amp=-\sqrt{\frac{81}{4}} \amp\text{ or }\amp\amp z\amp=\sqrt{\frac{81}{4}}</mrow>
                    <mrow>z\amp=-\frac{9}{2}\amp\text{ or }\amp\amp z\amp=\frac{9}{2}</mrow>
                </md>The solution set is <m>\{-\frac{9}{2},\frac{9}{2}\}</m>. </p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <p>We can also use the square root property to solve an equation that has a squared expression. We begin by isolating the squared expression.</p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Solve for <m>p</m> in <m>50=2(p-1)^2</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p><md>
                    <mrow>50\amp=2(p-1)^2</mrow>
                    <mrow>\divideunder{50}{2}\amp=\divideunder{2(p-1)^2}{2}</mrow>
                    <mrow>25\amp=(p-1)^2</mrow>
                    <intertext>Now that we have the squared expression isolated, we can use the square root property</intertext>
                    <mrow>(p-1)\amp=-\sqrt{25}\amp\text{or}\amp\amp(p-1)\amp=\sqrt{25}</mrow>
                    <mrow>p-1\amp=-5\amp\text{or}\amp\amp p-1\amp=5</mrow>
                    <mrow>p-1\addright{1}\amp=-5\addright{1}\amp\text{or}\amp\amp p-1\addright{1}\amp=5\addright{1}</mrow>
                    <mrow>p\amp=-4\amp\text{or}\amp\amp p\amp=6</mrow></md>
                    The solution set is <m>\{-4,6\}</m>. Let's check the solution <m>p=-4</m>:<md>
                    <mrow>50\amp=2(p-1)^2</mrow>
                    <mrow>50\amp\stackrel{?}{=}2(\substitute{-4}-1)^2</mrow>
                    <mrow>50\amp\stackrel{?}{=}2(-5)^2</mrow>
                    <mrow>50\amp\stackrel{?}{=}2(25)</mrow>
                    <mrow>50\amp\stackrel{\checkmark}{=}50</mrow>
                </md>The solution <m>p=-4</m> is correct. Checking <m>p=6</m> is left as an exercise.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <p>Sometimes the radicands are not perfect squares. Here is an example where we have a square root symbol in the solution and we need to simplify the square root.</p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Solve for <m>q</m> in <m>(q+2)^2-12=0</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p><md>
                    <mrow>(q+2)^2-12\amp=0</mrow>
                    <mrow>(q+2)^2\amp=12</mrow></md><md>
                    <mrow>(q+2)\amp=-\sqrt{12}\amp\text{or}\amp\amp(q+2)\amp=\sqrt{12}</mrow>
                    <mrow>q+2\amp=-2\sqrt{3}\amp\text{or}\amp\amp q+2\amp=2\sqrt{3}</mrow>
                    <mrow>q+2\subtractright{2}\amp=-2\sqrt{3}\subtractright{2}\amp\text{or}\amp\amp q+2\subtractright{2}\amp=2\sqrt{3}\subtractright{2}</mrow>
                    <mrow>q\amp=-2\sqrt{3}-2\amp\text{or}\amp\amp q\amp=2\sqrt{3}-2</mrow>
                </md>The solution set is <m>\{-2\sqrt{3}-2,2\sqrt{3}-2\}</m>.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <p>Remember that if a squre root is in the denominator then we need to rationalize it like we learned in <xref ref="section-square-root-properties">Section</xref>. We will need to rationalize the denominator in the next example.</p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Solve for <m>n</m> in <m>2n^2-3=0</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p><md>
                    <mrow>2n^2-3\amp=0</mrow>
                    <mrow>2n^2\amp=3</mrow>
                    <mrow>n^2\amp=\frac{3}{2}</mrow></md><md>
                    <mrow>n\amp=-\sqrt{\frac{3}{2}}\amp\text{or}\amp\amp n\amp=\sqrt{\frac{3}{2}}</mrow>
                    <mrow>n\amp=-\frac{\sqrt{3}}{\sqrt{2}} \amp\text{or}\amp\amp n\amp=\frac{\sqrt{3}}{\sqrt{2}}</mrow>
                    <mrow>n\amp=-\frac{\sqrt{3}\cdot\sqrt{2}}{\sqrt{2}\cdot\sqrt{2}} \amp\text{or}\amp\amp n\amp=\frac{\sqrt{3}\cdot\sqrt{2}}{\sqrt{2}\cdot\sqrt{2}}</mrow>
                    <mrow>n\amp=-\frac{\sqrt{6}}{2}\amp\text{ or }\amp\amp n\amp=\frac{\sqrt{6}}{2}</mrow>
                </md>The solution set is <m>\{-\frac{\sqrt{6}}{2},\frac{\sqrt{6}}{2}\}</m>.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <p>When the radicand is a negative number, there is no real solution. Here is an example of an equation with no real solution.</p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Solve for <m>x</m> in <m>x^2+49=0</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p><md>
                    <mrow>x^2+49\amp=0</mrow>
                    <mrow>x^2\amp=-49</mrow>
                </md>Since <m>\sqrt{-49}</m> is not a real number, we say the equation has no real solution. The solution set is <m>\{ \}</m> or <m>\emptyset</m>.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>
        </subsection>

       <subsection>
        <title>Pythagorean Theorem Applications</title>

        <p>Here are some more examples using the Pythagorean Theorem to find sides of triangles.</p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Find the missing length in this right triangle.</p>

                <figure>
                    <caption>a right triangle</caption>
                    <image width="35%">
                        <latex-image-code>
                            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                \draw (0,0) -- (3,0) -- (3,4) -- cycle;
                                \draw (3,0.2) -- (2.8,0.2) -- (2.8,0);
                                \draw [below] (1.5,0) node {$5$};
                                \draw [right] (3,2) node {$x$};
                                \draw (1,2) node {$10$};
                            \end{tikzpicture}]]>
                        </latex-image-code>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>We will use the Pythagorean Theorem to solve for <m>x</m>:<md>
                        <mrow>5^2+x^2\amp=10^2</mrow>
                        <mrow>25+x^2\amp=100</mrow>
                        <mrow>x^2\amp=75</mrow>
                        <mrow>x\amp=\sqrt{75}\amp\text{no need to consider }-\sqrt{75}\text{ in this context}</mrow>
                        <mrow>x\amp=\sqrt{25\cdot3}</mrow>
                        <mrow>x\amp=5\sqrt{3}</mrow>
                    </md>The missing length is <m>x=5\sqrt{3}</m>.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Scenario: A designer is designing a <m>50</m>-inch TV, which implies the diagonal of the TV's screen will be <m>50</m> inches long. The screen's length to width ratio will be <m>4:3</m>. Find the TV screen's length and width.</p>

                <p>Since the screen's length to width ratio will be <m>4:3</m>, assume the screen's length is <m>4x</m> inches, and its width is <m>3x</m> inches. We will draw a diagram.</p>

            <figure>
                <caption>Pythagorean Theorem Problem</caption>
                <image width="50%">
                    <latex-image-code>
                        <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                            \draw (0,0) rectangle (4,3);
                            \draw (0,0) -- (4,3);
                            \draw [below] (2,0) node {$a=4x$ in};
                            \draw [right] (4,1.5) node {$b=3x$ in};
                            \draw [center] (2,1.5) node {$c=50$ in};
                        \end{tikzpicture}]]>
                    </latex-image-code>
                </image>
            </figure>
            </statement>

            <solution>
            <p>Now we can use Pythagorean Theoream to write and solve an equation:<md>
                <mrow>a^2+b^2\amp=c^2</mrow>
                <mrow>(4x)^2+(3x)^2\amp=50^2</mrow>
                <mrow>16x^2+9x^2\amp=2500</mrow>
                <mrow>25x^2\amp=2500</mrow>
                <mrow>\divideunder{25x^2}{25}\amp=\divideunder{2500}{25}</mrow>
                <mrow>x^2\amp=100</mrow>
                <mrow>x^2\amp=\sqrt{100}</mrow>
                <mrow>x\amp=10</mrow>
            </md>Solution: Since <m>x=10</m>, the screen's length is <m>4x=4(10)=40</m> inches, and its width is <m>3x=3(10)=30</m> inches.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>
    </subsection>

